In [6]:
# A piecewise constant function
def _G(x, v, b):
    g = v[0]
    idx = 1
    while idx<len(b) and x>b[idx]:
        #print(idx)
        g = v[idx]
        idx +=1
    return g

def G(x, v, b):
    val = [_G(y, v, b) for y in x]
    return np.array(val)

Fit $f(x)$ with a piecewise constant function¶

Logistic Functions¶

In [9]:
def logistic(x, w, b):
    g = 1./(1.+np.exp(w*(b-np.array(x))))
    return g

Making a bump out of 2 logistic functions¶

In [10]:
xx = np.linspace(0, 1, 400)
plt.plot(xx, logistic(xx, 50, 0.4));
plt.plot(xx, 1.-logistic(xx, 50, 0.4));
In [11]:
def bump(x, b, delta):
    return logistic(x,1./delta,b-delta) -logistic(x,1./delta,b+delta)
In [12]:
plt.plot(xx, bump(xx, 0.4, 0.02));

Least squares fit of a combination of bumps¶

A small number of bumps¶

In [13]:
N = 6
b = np.linspace(0, 1, N, endpoint=True)
In [14]:
A = np.zeros([len(xx), len(b)])
for idx,bb in enumerate(b):
    regressor = bump(xx, bb, 0.5/(N-1))
    A[:,idx] = regressor

c = np.linalg.lstsq(A, f(xx), rcond=-1)[0]

ff_diag = A @ np.diag(c)
ff = A @ c
In [15]:
plt.plot(xx, f(xx), 'b', linewidth=3)
plt.plot(xx, ff_diag);
In [16]:
plt.plot(xx, f(xx))
plt.plot(xx, ff);
max_diff = np.max(abs(ff-f(xx)))
plt.title('Max error = '+str(max_diff));

Least squares fit of a combination of logistics¶

We can mimic the piecewise constant¶

In [21]:
N = 21
b = np.linspace(0, 1, N, endpoint=True)
In [22]:
A = np.zeros([len(xx), 2*len(b)])
w = 500.
for idx,bb in enumerate(b):
    regressor = logistic(xx, w, bb)
    A[:,2*idx] = regressor
    rev = logistic(xx, -w, bb)
    A[:,2*idx+1] = rev

c = np.linalg.lstsq(A, f(xx), rcond=-1)[0]

ff_diag = A @ np.diag(c)
ff = A @ c
In [23]:
plt.plot(xx, f(xx), 'b', linewidth=3)
plt.plot(xx, A);
In [24]:
plt.plot(xx, f(xx))
plt.plot(xx, ff);
max_diff = np.max(abs(ff-f(xx)))
plt.title('Max error = '+str(max_diff));
